The System You’re Pointing At

Implication Scout Layer (ISL)

Think of each “imp” as a bounded agent with a job:

explore one path, return signal, don’t get lost

⸻

1) What an “Imp” Actually Is

Each imp = a small, constrained evaluator:
	•	Input: a statement / image / idea
	•	Task: follow one implication path
	•	Output:
	•	interpretation
	•	confidence
	•	usefulness score
	•	risk flag
	•	novelty score

They don’t decide truth.

They map terrain.

⸻

2) Types of Imps (Pantheon-aligned)

You don’t want identical scouts—you want specialization.

🔍 Structural Imp
	•	What pattern is this?
	•	Maps invariants (your favorite layer)

🧭 Causal Imp
	•	What happens next if this is true?
	•	Builds forward chains

⚖️ Risk Imp (Hound-aligned)
	•	What breaks?
	•	What goes wrong?

💰 Value Imp (Goblin-aligned)
	•	Where is leverage?
	•	Where is mispricing?

🪞 Mirror Imp
	•	Is this coherent or self-deceptive?
	•	Checks integrity

🕸️ Spider Imp
	•	How does this connect to other domains?

⸻

3) The Core Mechanic (this is your real idea)

You said:

“use the time it takes for clarity to reach threshold”

That’s the gold.

Each path gets:
	•	t_clarity → how long until it stabilizes
	•	Δclarity rate → how fast it becomes coherent
	•	drift → how much it mutates while explored

⸻

Why this matters

Fast clarity ≠ correct
Slow clarity ≠ wrong

But:

stable clarity under pressure = high-value signal

